Ansible for Site Reliability Engineering (SRE)

This section explains Ansible from beginner to advanced level, aligned with how a Senior SRE actually uses it in production environments.

Ansible is one of the most important tools for:

Infrastructure automation
Configuration management
Server provisioning
Incident response automation
Platform standardization
Large-scale fleet management

A Senior SRE uses Ansible to ensure:

Systems are reproducible
Deployments are consistent
Configuration drift is eliminated
Infrastructure is recoverable
1. What Ansible Is

Ansible is an agentless automation tool that uses SSH to manage remote systems.

Architecture:

Control Node (Ansible installed)
        |
        | SSH
        v
Managed Nodes (Servers)

Ansible executes tasks using:

Modules
Playbooks
Inventory files
2. Ansible Core Concepts
Inventory

Defines the systems Ansible will manage.

Default location:

/etc/ansible/hosts

Example:

[webservers]
10.0.0.10
10.0.0.11

[dbservers]
10.0.0.20
10.0.0.21

You can also define ranges:

10.0.0.[10:20]

Check inventory:

ansible-inventory --list
3. Ansible Playbooks

A playbook is a YAML file that defines automation tasks.

Example structure:

---
- name: Example Playbook
  hosts: all
  become: yes

  tasks:
    - name: Install Apache
      yum:
        name: httpd
        state: present

    - name: Start Apache
      service:
        name: httpd
        state: started

Key components:

Field	Description
hosts	Target machines
become	Run as elevated user
tasks	Actions to execute
modules	Tools like yum, service, copy
4. First Playbook (Connectivity Test)

Create directory:

mkdir -p /etc/ansible/playbooks
cd /etc/ansible/playbooks

Create file:

vi first.yml

Playbook:

---
- name: My first playbook
  hosts: localhost

  tasks:
    - name: Test connectivity
      ping:

Validate syntax:

ansible-playbook --syntax-check first.yml

Dry run:

ansible-playbook --check first.yml

Run:

ansible-playbook first.yml
