18. Ad-Hoc Commands (Important for SRE)

Used for quick operations during incidents.

General syntax:

ansible [target] -m [module] -a "options"

Examples:

Ping all servers:

ansible all -m ping

Create file:

ansible all -m file -a "path=/home/jeff/file state=touch mode=700"

Install package:

ansible all -m yum -a "name=telnet state=present"

Start service:

ansible all -m service -a "name=httpd state=started"

Reboot server:

ansible all -a "/sbin/reboot"

Gather system information:

ansible all -m setup

Senior SRE use cases:

Emergency fixes
Fleet diagnostics
Bulk operations
Rapid incident mitigation
19. Roles (Production-Grade Automation)

Roles make playbooks modular and reusable.

Directory structure:

roles/
   apache/
      tasks/
         main.yml
   ntpd/
      tasks/
         main.yml
   named/
      tasks/
         main.yml

Example role task:

roles/apache/tasks/main.yml
---
- name: Install Apache
  yum:
    name: httpd
    state: present

- name: Start Apache
  service:
    name: httpd
    state: started

Main playbook:

---
- name: Install infrastructure packages
  hosts: all

  roles:
    - apache
    - ntpd
    - named

This is how production environments structure Ansible repos.

